03968nam a22005895i 9781478023708DE-B159720230103011142.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230103t20222022ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814780237087 a10.1515/97814780237082doi  a(DE-B1597)642224  a(OCoLC)1348489972  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aSOC0010002bisacsh04a391.5089/96223//eng/20220701eng1 aCobb, Jasmine Nichole, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNew Growth :bThe Art and Texture of Black Hair /cJasmine Nichole Cobb. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Visual Arts of Africa and its Diasporas : 4300tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tINTRODUCTION, NEW GROWTH: BLACK HAIR AND LIBERATION -- t1 ARCHIVE. SLAVERY, SENTIMENT, AND FEELING -- t2 TEXTURE. THE COARSENESS OF RACIAL CAPITALISM -- t3 TOUCH. CAMERA IMAGES AND CONTACT REVISIONS -- t4. SURFACE. THE ART OF BLACK HAIR -- tCONCLUSION. CROWNING GESTURES -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom Frederick Douglass to Angela Davis, “natural hair” has been associated with the Black freedom struggle. In New Growth Jasmine Nichole Cobb traces the history of Afro-textured coiffure, exploring it as a visual material through which to reimagine the sensual experience of Blackness. Through close readings of slave narratives, scrapbooks, travel illustrations, documentary films, and photography as well as collage, craft, and sculpture, from the nineteenth century to the present, Cobb shows how the racial distinctions ascribed to people of African descent become simultaneously visible and tactile. Whether examining Soul Train’s and Ebony’s promotion of the Afro hairstyle alongside styling products or how artists such as Alison Saar and Lorna Simpson underscore the construction of Blackness through the representation of hair, Cobb foregrounds the inseparability of Black hair’s look and feel. Demonstrating that Blackness is palpable through appearance and feeling, Cobb reveals the various ways that people of African descent forge new relationships to the body, public space, and visual culture through the embrace of Black hair.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 0aAfrican AmericansxRace identity. 0aBlack peoplexRace identity. 0aHairdressing of African AmericansxHistory. 0aHairdressing of African AmericansxSocial aspects. 0aHairdressing of Black peoplexHistory. 0aHairdressing of Black peoplexSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076691240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478023708?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478023708423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478023708/original  a978-3-11-076691-2  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles